issue.body:
For my specific case, I have a `::test()` method on my Event classes. This `::test()` method returns a factory I can use to easily build variations of the Event for testing purposes. However, both the factory classes and the `::test()` method itself do not need to be counted for code coverage.

My desired results:

 * Do not include any of the Event factories in code coverage
 * Do not include any of the Event `::test()` methods in code coverage
 * Not be required to specify concrete implementations in concrete tests

----

Here is my code:

```php
/**
 * @template T of TestObject
 */
interface EventWithTestFactory
{
    /**
     * @phpstan-return TestObject<T>
     */
    public static function test(): object;
}
```

```php
/**
 * @extends TestObject<ConversationUnblocked>
 */
class ConversationUnblockedFactory extends TestObject
{
    public static function new(): self
    {
        return self::ofType(ConversationUnblocked::class);
    }

    /**
     * @throws \ReflectionException
     */
    public function partial(
        ?ConversationId $conversationId = null
    ): self {
        return $this
            ->fromPartial(func_get_args())
            ->withDefaults(self::defaultDefinition(...));
    }

    public static function defaultDefinition(): array
    {
        return [
            'conversationId' => ConversationId::generate(...),
        ];
    }

    public function withConversationId(ConversationId $conversationId): self
    {
        return $this->withDefaults(['conversationId' => $conversationId]);
    }
}
```

```php
/**
 * @implements EventWithTestFactory<ConversationUnblockedFactory>
 */
final readonly class ConversationUnblocked implements Event, EventWithTestFactory
{
    use EdgeAwareReflectionSerializing;

    public function __construct(
    ) {
    }

    public static function test(): ConversationUnblockedFactory
    {
        return ConversationUnblockedFactory::new();
    }
}
```

My tests extend a base test case for each group of Events, depending on domain:


```php
abstract class ConversationTestCase extends TestCase
{
    // ...
}
```

```php
final class UnblockConversationTest extends ConversationTestCase
{
    // ...
}
```

----

The only way I've been able to get this to work is to define concrete class names in the actual test object like this:

```php
#[IgnoreClassForCodeCoverage(ConversationUnblockedFactory::class)]
#[IgnoreMethodForCodeCoverage(ConversationUnblocked::class, 'test')]
final class UnblockConversationTest extends ConversationTestCase
{
    // ...
}
```

Since I have several domains and dozens of events, what I hoped to was leverage the testing base classes and the interfaces/base classes for the code I want to ignore in coverage so that I just need to do the following:

```php
#[IgnoreClassForCodeCoverage(TestObject::class)]
#[IgnoreMethodForCodeCoverage(EventWithTestFactory::class, 'test')]
abstract class ConversationTestCase extends TestCase
{
    // ...
}
```

----

TL;DR

 * It looks like the attributes are not inherited by the concrete test cases.
 * It looks like the class specified in the attributes has to match the class name exactly (and not simply be an instance or implementation of).

Is it feasible or doable to address either of these points? Is there *another* way for me to do this with the current version of PHPUnit that isn't deprecated?

Is there a way to globally configure classes or interfaces – or specific methods on these – that can be ignored by code coverage?

| Q                         | A
| --------------------------| ---------------
| php-code-coverage version | 10.1.3
| PHP version               | 8.2.9
| Driver                    | Xdebug
| Xdebug version (if used)  | 3.2.2
| Installation Method       | Composer
| Usage Method              | PHPUnit
| PHPUnit version (if used) | 10.3.2

Deprecated `@CodeCoverageIgnore` removes the class from coverage report, but new attributes don't.

### OK - Example with deprecated @CodeCoverageIgnore
```
<?php

declare(strict_types=1);

namespace App\Utils;

use PHPUnit\Framework\Attributes\CodeCoverageIgnore;

#[CodeCoverageIgnore]
class Email
{
    public static function normalize(string $email): string
    {
        return strtolower(trim($email));
    }
}
```

